    "sessionSummary": [
      "Alcohols have -OH on aliphatic carbons; Phenols have it directly on a benzene ring.",
      "IUPAC naming requires the longest chain containing C-OH, numbered to give OH lowest locant.",
      "Classification (1°, 2°, 3°) depends on carbon substitution at the hydroxyl-bearing carbon."
    ],
    "nextSessionBridge": [
      "Today we learned structure and names. Tomorrow, we will explore how these structures affect physical properties like boiling points due to hydrogen bonding."
    ]
  },
  "studentLessonNotes": {
    "title": "Alcohols & Phenols: Structure & Naming",
    "introduction": "Welcome to the chapter on Alcohols, Phenols, and Ethers! You already know about functional groups. Today we dive into compounds containing the hydroxyl (-OH) group. But not all -OH groups are created equal!",
    "learningObjectives": [
      "Distinguish between alcohols and phenols based on structure.",
      "Apply IUPAC rules to name mono-hydric alcohols and phenols correctly.",
      "Classify alcohols as primary, secondary, or tertiary."
    ],
    "quickRecall": [
      "What is a functional group?",
      "How do you number the longest carbon chain?"
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Alcohols vs. Phenols",
        "explanation": "Both contain an -OH (hydroxyl) group, but their attachment point changes everything.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Alcohol: -OH attached to a saturated aliphatic carbon chain (sp3 hybridized). Example: Ethanol.",
          "Phenol: -OH attached directly to a benzene ring (aromatic system). The C-OH bond is stronger and has partial double bond character."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "Ethanol (CH3-CH2-OH) -> Alcohol",
          "Phenol (C6H5-OH) -> Phenol"
        ],
        "whyItMatters": "This distinction is the first step in predicting chemical reactions. They behave differently!",
        "terminology": [
          "Hydroxyl group (-OH)",
          "Aliphatic",
          "Aromatic ring"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "In alcohols, the carbon holding the OH is part of a chain or branch. In phenols, it's an integral part of the benzene ring itself.",
        "observedIn": [
          "Chemical tests (e.g., reaction with Na metal)",
          "Acidity differences"
        ],
        "visualSupport": [
          "Diagram showing C-OH in a chain vs. C-OH on a hexagon."
        ],
        "importantNotes": [
          "Benzyl alcohol is an ALCOHOL, not a phenol! The OH is attached to the CH2 group next to the ring, not directly to it."
        ],
        "memoryTechniques": [
          "'Phen'ol = 'Phenomenal' aromatic connection (Directly on Ring)."
        ],
        "conceptSummary": [
          "Alcohol: -OH on chain. Phenol: -OH on ring."
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "IUPAC Nomenclature",
        "explanation": "Naming follows specific rules to ensure every chemist knows exactly which molecule you mean.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Select the longest carbon chain containing the -OH group.",
          "Number the chain starting from the end nearest to the -OH group (lowest locant).",
          "Replace the suffix '-e' of the alkane with '-ol'.",
          "Indicate the position of the OH group by a number before the name."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "CH3-CH2-OH -> Ethanol (not 1-Ethanol, as '1' is implied for terminal).",
          "CH3-CH(OH)-CH3 -> Propan-2-ol.",
          "C6H5-OH -> Phenol."
        ],
        "whyItMatters": "Correct naming is essential for writing reaction equations and solving synthesis problems in exams.",
        "terminology": [
          "Locant",
          "Suffix"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "If there are multiple functional groups, priority rules apply (OH > Alkyl). For phenols, the carbon with OH is always C-1 unless a higher priority group exists.",
        "observedIn": [
          "Chemical nomenclature in textbooks and papers."
        ],
        "visualSupport": [
          "Numbering arrows on chain diagrams."
        ],
        "importantNotes": [
          "Do not use '1' for simple alcohols like ethanol or propan-2-ol unless necessary to avoid ambiguity, but strictly speaking, it's part of the rule. For phenol, no number is needed as OH is always at position 1."
        ],
        "memoryTechniques": [
          "'Ol' replaces 'e'. Count from the side closest to the party (OH)."
        ],
        "conceptSummary": [
          "Longest chain + Lowest Number for OH = -ol suffix."
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Classification of Alcohols",
        "explanation": "Alcohols are grouped by how many other carbon atoms are attached to the one holding the OH.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Primary (1°): The C-OH is attached to 0 or 1 Carbon atom. (e.g., Ethanol, Propan-1-ol).",
          "Secondary (2°): The C-OH is attached to 2 Carbon atoms. (e.g., Propan-2-ol).",
          "Tertiary (3°): The C-OH is attached to 3 Carbon atoms. (e.g., tert-Butyl alcohol)."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "1-Propanol: CH3-CH2-CH2-OH -> Primary.",
          "2-Propanol: CH3-CH(OH)-CH3 -> Secondary.",
          "(CH3)3C-OH -> Tertiary."
        ],
        "whyItMatters": "This classification predicts how the alcohol will react (e.g., oxidation, dehydration).",
        "terminology": [
          "Primary/Secondary/Tertiary"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "Look at the carbon atom bonded to the oxygen. Count only the carbons directly attached to it.",
        "observedIn": [
          "Reaction mechanisms (SN1/SN2, Oxidation)."
        ],
        "visualSupport": [
          "Tree diagram showing branching."
        ],
        "importantNotes": [
          "Methanol is a special case but often grouped with primary alcohols in reactivity discussions due to having only one carbon."
        ],
        "memoryTechniques": [
          "1° = 1 neighbor (or 0). 2° = 2 neighbors. 3° = 3 neighbors."
        ],
        "conceptSummary": [
          "Count the carbons attached to C-OH: 1, 2, or 3 determines class."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "definitions": [
      {
        "term": "Alcohol",
        "definition": "Organic compounds where a hydroxyl group (-OH) is bonded to an aliphatic carbon atom."
      },
      {
        "term": "Phenol",
        "definition": "Compounds containing a hydroxyl group directly attached to an aromatic benzene ring."
      }
    ],
    "workedExamples": [
      {
        "title": "Naming and Classifying 3-Methylbutan-2-ol",
        "steps": [
          "Identify the longest chain containing OH: It is a 4-carbon chain (Butane).",
          "Number from end nearest OH: Numbering starts left to right so OH gets position 2.",
          "Name parent: Butan-2-ol.",
          "Add substituent: Methyl group at C3 -> 3-Methylbutan-2-ol.",
          "Classify: The carbon with OH (C2) is attached to two other carbons (C1 and C3).",
          "Conclusion: It is a Secondary alcohol."
        ],
        "explanation": "Always prioritize the functional group for numbering. Classification depends solely on the immediate neighbors of the hydroxyl-bearing carbon."
      }
    ],
    "revisionSection": {
      "definitions": [
        "Alcohol: -OH on aliphatic C.",
        "Phenol: -OH directly on benzene ring."
      ],
      "formulas": [],
      "facts": [
        "Methanol is the simplest alcohol (CH3OH).",
        "Ethanol is commonly known as 'grain alcohol' or spirit."
