      "Classify 1-Methylcyclohexanol as primary, secondary, or tertiary."
    ],
    "didYouKnow": [
      "Phenols were among the first antiseptics used in surgery by Joseph Lister!"
    ],
    "summary": [
      "Today we learned to identify and name alcohols and phenols. Remember: Structure determines function."
    ],
    "quickRevision": [
      "Check your ability to draw 1°, 2°, and 3° structures from names instantly."
    ]
  },
  "learningOutcomes": [
    "LO1: Students will be able to differentiate between alcohols and phenols based on the hybridization of the carbon atom attached to the hydroxyl group.",
    "LO2: Students will apply IUPAC nomenclature rules correctly to name mono-hydric alcohols and phenols, including handling branched chains.",
    "LO3: Students will classify given alcohol structures as primary (1°), secondary (2°), or tertiary (3°) based on carbon substitution."
  ],
  "introduction": "Imagine you have two bottles. One contains a liquid that makes you feel warm and is used in hand sanitizers; the other is a white crystalline solid with a distinct medicinal smell, historically used to treat wounds. Both contain an -OH group! What if I told you these are chemically very different? Today, we unlock the secret code of organic chemistry: how the position of that single -OH group changes everything.",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "This session introduces the fundamental structural differences between alcohols and phenols. Alcohols feature a hydroxyl group attached to an sp3 hybridized carbon in an alkane chain, while phenols have it directly bonded to an aromatic benzene ring. We will master the IUPAC naming conventions for these compounds and learn how to classify them as primary, secondary, or tertiary based on their structure.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Alcohols: -OH attached to aliphatic (sp3) carbon; Phenols: -OH directly attached to benzene ring (aromatic).",
      "IUPAC Naming: Longest chain containing C-OH, lowest number for OH suffix '-ol'.",
      "Classification: 1° (0/1 neighbor), 2° (2 neighbors), 3° (3 neighbors) based on the carbon bearing -OH."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "The chapter begins by distinguishing two major classes of hydroxy compounds. Alcohols are derivatives of alkanes where a hydrogen is replaced by an OH group. The general formula for saturated mono-hydric alcohols is CnH2n+1OH. Phenols, however, are distinct because the -OH group is directly attached to the benzene ring (C6H5-OH). This direct attachment creates resonance effects that make phenols more acidic than alcohols, a topic we will explore later.\n\nNomenclature follows strict IUPAC rules: identify the longest carbon chain containing the hydroxyl-bearing carbon. Number this chain to give the -OH group the lowest possible locant (number). The suffix '-e' of the parent alkane is replaced by '-ol'. For example, CH3-CH2-OH becomes Ethanol. If there are substituents like methyl groups, they are named as prefixes with their position numbers.\n\nClassification is critical for predicting reactivity. We look at the carbon atom bonded to the oxygen (the carbinol carbon). If this carbon is attached to only one other carbon (or zero in methanol), it's a primary alcohol. Attached to two carbons? Secondary. Attached to three? Tertiary. This classification dictates how they undergo oxidation and dehydration reactions."
  },
